@node Creating a Component
@section Creating a Component

Three types of component can be defined in Dezyne:

@itemize

@item     The first type is a component that has only a name defined and has no implementation.  In Dezyne this is
        a placeholder for a component that is implemented in another programming language.

@item     The second type is a component that has an implementation marked by the ‘behaviour’ keyword.

@item     The third type is a component decomposed into others that has an implementation marked by the 'system' keyword.  The system specifies contained component instances, see further
@ref{Decomposing a Component},.
@end itemize

@menu
* Component Syntax::
* Importing Models::
* Ports::
* External::
* Injected::
* Behaviour::
@end menu

@node Component Syntax
@subsection Component Syntax

A component declaration is named, and introduces a list of provides and
requires interfaces and optionally behaviour or a system.

@example
1) component CompName
   // placeholder for component implemented in another programming language
   @{
     provides CompInterface compinterface; // list of provided interfaces
     requires UsedInterface usedinterface; // list of required interfaces
    @}
@end example

@example
2) component CompName
   @{
   // component with behaviour
     provides CompInterface compinterface; // list of provided interfaces
     requires UsedInterface usedinterface; // list of required interfaces
     behaviour   // behaviour
     @{ ...  @}
   @}
@end example

@example
3) component CompName
   @{
   // system component
     provides CompInterface compinterface; // list of provided interfaces
     requires UsedInterface usedinterface; // list of required interfaces
     system   // system
     @{ ...  @}
   @}
@end example

@subsubsection Examples

@subsubsection A component that will be implemented in another programming language

  This component has no implementation.  It represents
  a component implemented in another programming language.


@example
component CompName
@{
  provides CompInterface compinterface;
@}
@end example

@subsubsection A Component Implementing One Interface and a Simple Behaviour

The following component implements one interface and a straightforward
behaviour section.

@example
component Leaf
@{
  provides ISensor ctrl;
    behaviour
    @{
        on ctrl.event(): @{ @}
    @}
@}
@end example

@subsubsection A Component Decomposed Into Two Components

A component decomposed into two components where these components are
connected via their ports.

@example
component Composition
@{
  provides CompInterface compinterface;
  system
  @{
    Comp1 comp1instance;
    Comp2 comp2instance;
    comp1instance.port1 <=> comp2instance.port2;
  @}
@}
@end example

