@node Using Conditional Statements
@subsection Using Conditional Statements

    Conditional statements (if-else) can be used to program decision making on which actions
    to perform

@subsubsection Syntax

    The keyword if is used for a simple conditional statement:

@example
if (expression) statement-true;
@end example

    In this case when the expression is true then statement-true will be executed.

    An if-else construction can be used for programming more elaborate decisions.

@example
if (expression) statement-true;
else statement-false;
@end example

    if the expression is true then statement-true will be executed, else
    statement-true is skipped and statement-false is executed.

@subsubsection Examples

@subsubsection A basic if-else example

This example shows an interface with a behaviour section where if else
is used to select the actions to be performed based on the value of
a state and a local variable.

@example
interface IImperativeAction
@{
  in void doIt();
  out void done();
  out void skip();
  behaviour
  @{
    enum Toggle @{Ping, Pong@};
    Toggle state = Toggle.Ping;
    on doIt:
    @{
      bool localVariable = false;
      if (state.Ping)
      @{
        localVariable = true;
      @}
      else
      @{
        localVariable = (state == Toggle.Ping);
      @}
      if (localVariable)
      @{
        done;
        state = Toggle.Pong;
      @}
      else
      @{
        skip;
        state = Toggle.Ping;
      @}
    @}
  @}
@}
@end example

