@item @ref{Thread-safe Shell},
@end itemize

@node Decomposing a Component
@section Decomposing a Component

A component can be decomposed into a group of components.  A grouping of
components is called a @b{@i{system}}.  A component that is decomposed
into a system has no own behaviour definition, the behaviour of the
system is defined by the component into which it is decomposed.

@menu
* Systems of Components::
* Specifying Ports::
* Binding Ports::
@end menu

@node Systems of Components
@subsection Systems of Components

The components within a system can also be composite components, so it
is possible to define systems of systems.

Composite components can also expose ports of contained components by
binding their own provided or required ports to ports of contained
components.  In that case the binding looks like

@example
port <=> component1_instance_name.port
@end example


@subsubsection Syntax

The keyword @b{@i{system}} is used to define a composition.  Inside the
system definition the instances of the components that are contained in
the system are specified.

To define a system inside the composite component use:

@example
component Composition
@{
  system
  @{
    Component1 component1instance;
    Component2 component2instance;
// binding of the components:
// where Component1 provides or requires port1
// and Component2 requires or provides port1
    component1instance.port1 <=> component2instance.port1;
  @}
@}
@end example

Within a system components have to be connected together.  A binding statement takes the form of
@example
component1_instance_name.port <=> component2_instance_name.port
@end example

Only ports with an equal interface definition and opposite direction can
be bound together.

Composite components can also expose ports of contained components by
binding their own provided or required ports to ports of contained
components.  In that case the binding looks like

@example
port <=> component1_instance_name.port
@end example

@example
component Composition
@{
  provides Interface1 port1;
  system
  @{
    Component1 component1instance;
    Component2 component2instance;
// binding of the components:
// where Component1 provides port1;
// where Component1 provides or requires port2
// and Component2 requires or provides port2
    port1 <=> component1instance1.port1
    component1instance.port2 <=> component2instance.port2;
  @}
@}
@end example

@subsubsection Examples

@subsubsection Decomposition into components and binding their ports.

Here a component is decomposed into two other components C1 and C2.

@example
interface I1
@{
  in void event();
@}
component C1
@{
  provides I1 i1;
@}
component C2
@{
  requires I1 i1;
@}
component Decomposition
@{
  system
  @{
    C1 c1;
    C2 c2;
    c1.i1 <=> c2.i1;
  @}
@}
@end example

@subsubsection Exposing ports

Here a component is decomposed into two other components C1 and C2 and
the interface provided by component C2 is exposed.

@example
interface I1
@{
  in void event();
@}
interface I2
@{
  in void event();
@}
component C1
@{
  provides I1 i1;
@}
component C2
@{
  provides I2 i2;
  requires I1 i1;
@}
component Decomposition
@{
  provides I2 i2Proxy;
  system
  @{
    C1 c1;
    C2 c2;
    i2Proxy <=> c2.i2;
    c1.i1 <=> c2.i1;
  @}
@}
@end example

