@node Interface and Component Behaviour
@section Interface and Component Behaviour

A behaviour description might look like this:


@example
behaviour
@{
  enum MyEnumType @{ Value1, Value2 @};
  MyEnumType myEnumVariable = MyEnumType.Value1;
  bool myBoolVariable = true;
  on myPort1.myEvent1():
  @{
    bool blocal = myBoolVariable;
    myBoolVariable = false;
    myPort2.myEvent2();
    f(blocal);
  @}
  [myEnumVariable.Value2]
  @{
    on myPort1.myEvent2(): illegal;
  @}
  void f(bool b)
  @{
    if (b) myPort2.myEvent5();
    else   @{ myPort2.myEvent5(); myBoolVariable = true; @}
  @}
@}
@end example


This behaviour section introduces a local enum type (@code{MyEnumType}),
two variables (called @code{myEnumVariable} and @code{myBoolVariable}),
a number of statements, and a function definition (@code{void f(bool b)}) with one parameter.
Note that in a sub scope a local variable @code{blocal} is defined.
The different constructs are handled in more detail below.

@subsection Variable Declarations

As demonstrated in the example above, variables can be defined in a
behaviour description, both at top level and in a local scope.  Variables
must be given an initial value.

The top-level variables are often referred to as 'state variables'.
Their scope extends to the complete behaviour description, including the
body of functions defined in the behaviour.


Variables defined at other places have a scope which is restricted to the compound statement
(@code{@{ ....  @}}) they are defined in.

@subsubsection State Variables

@subsection Declarative versus Imperative Statements

There are two 'kinds' of behavioural statements: 'declarative' and
'imperative'.  The declarative part describes the trigger events and the
conditions in which they have to be handled, while the imperative part
describes the response that has to occur as result of a trigger.

@subsection Compound Statement
Statements of the same 'kind' can be grouped using curly braces:



@example
  @{ Statement1; Statement2; Statement3; @}
@end example


It results in a single 'compound statement', of the same 'kind' as its
sub statements, and can be used as such.
Note that the list of statements within the curly braces can be empty:



@example
  @{ /* this is an empty statement sequence */ @}
@end example



@subsection Declarative Statements
The triggers an interface or component has to handle and the conditions
in which they occur are described as declarative statements.
The conditions are expressed as 'guard statements', the triggers as
'on-event statements'.

@subsubsection Guard Statement
A guard statement looks like:



@example
  [ myBooleanExpression ] myStatement
@end example


The square brackets (@code{[} and @code{]}) must contain a boolean expression
expressing the validity of the guard.  The statement following the guard can be either
declarative or imperative.

@subsubsection On-event Statement
In an interface behaviour specification an on-event statement is expressed as:



@example
  on myEvent: myStatement
@end example


The statement contains a keyword @code{on}, the name of an event
introduced in the interface, a colon (@code{:}), and a statement,
which can be either be declarative or imperative.
A declarative statement must not contain further on-event statements:
nesting these statements is not allowed.


Note that no event parameters must be specified in an interface.


In a component behaviour specification an on-event statement is expressed as:



@example
  on myPort.myEvent(myParameter1): myStatement
@end example


where @code{myPort} is a port of the component with an interface type
that contains event @code{myEvent} with one data parameter.
Note that in a component behaviour specification data parameters have to be used where specified.
On the trigger each data parameter must be a fresh variable,
implicitly typed conform the event specification.

@subsection Imperative Statements
The response on a (guarded) trigger event are expressed in the imperative
statement following the declarative part.
All variable assignments,  event actions, function calls, etc.  are handled here.

@subsubsection Variable Declaration Statement
New variables can be declared as follows:



@example
  myType myVariable = myInitialValueExpression;
@end example


where @code{myType} denotes a previously defined type,
@code{myVariable} is a 'fresh' name, and
@code{myInitialValueExpression} an expression of type
@code{myType}.


After the variable has been declared it can be referred to as long as the
referring place is in scope (scopes being introduced by compounds).
'Fresh' should be interpreted as follows:

@itemize

@item No two variables with the same name can be declared in one scope.
@item A variable @code{myVar} that has been declared in a wider scope
can be 'shadowed' by a variable declaration with the same name in a sub scope
@end itemize

@subsubsection Assignment Statement
A previously declared variable can change value using an assignment statement:



@example
  myVariable = myValueExpression;
@end example



@subsubsection Action Statement
In handling the response on a trigger event, an event action can be called.
The syntax in an interface declaration is:



@example
  myEvent;
@end example


where @code{myEvent} is the name of an out event introduced in the interface.
Note that no event parameters must be specified.


In a component behaviour specification an action statement is expressed as:



@example
  myPort.myEvent(myParameterExpression);
@end example


where @code{myPort} is a port of the component with an interface type
that contains event @code{myEvent} with one data parameter.


Note that the event in an action statement must be a void event.
For a valued event the return value must be caught, so an
assignment statement is the appropriate way to handle that:



@example
  myVariable = myEvent;
@end example


or



@example
  myVariable = myPort.myEvent(myParameterExpression);
@end example


in an interface or component behaviour respectively.

@subsubsection Function Call Statement
A function defined in a behavioral specification can be called with
properly typed parameter expressions.  Given a function declaration



@example
  void myFunc(MyEnumType e, bool b) @{ /* ...  */ @}
@end example


a function call statement might look like:



@example
  myFunc(myEnumExpression, myBooleanExpression);
@end example


Note that the function in a function call statement must be a void function.
For a valued function the return value must be caught, so an
assignment statement is the appropriate way to handle that:



@example
  myVariable = myValuedFunc(myBooleanExpression);
@end example



@subsubsection Reply Statement
A valued trigger event will have to set the appropriate return value in
its response handling.  Setting that value (not returning yet) is denoted as:



@example
  reply(myValueExpression);
@end example



@subsubsection Return Statement
A valued function has to return with a value of the appropriate type.
This looks like:



@example
  return myValuedExpression;
@end example



@subsubsection If Statement
Conditional handling of statements is supported by the if statement,
which can have an optional else part:



@example
  if (myBooleanExpression) myStatement1
@end example


or:



@example
  if (myBooleanExpression) myStatement1 else myStatement2
@end example


where @code{if} and @code{else} are keywords,
and the parentheses are part of the construct.
The expression between the parentheses must be a boolean expression.
The statements @code{myStatement1} and  @code{myStatement2}are arbitrary imperative statements.


Note that nested if statements are allowed, and that



@example
  if (b1) if (b2) myStatement1 else myStatement2
@end example


will be interpreted as



@example
  if (b1)
  @{ if (b2) myStatement1 else myStatement2 @}
@end example


and not as



@example
  if (b1)
  @{ if (b2) myStatement1 @}
  else myStatement2
@end example


In other words: @code{else} binds to the closest if.

@subsection Functions

A function declaration introduces the signature of a function and its
body.  The signature is built up from the return type, the name of the
function, and a list of typed parameters.  The body is a compound
statement in the imperative part of the language, so no on-event and
guarded statements are allowed.  It is allowed however to refer to
action events and global state variables, and of course to the function
parameters.


An example:



@example
MyReturnType myFunc(bool myPar1, MyEnum myPar2)
@{
  bool myLocalBool = myPar2;
  if (myPar1)
  @{
    myPort.myAction();
    myLocalBool = false;
  @}
  myGlobal = myPar2;
  myOtherFunc(myLocalBool);
  return myRetuenValue;
@}
@end example


This declares a function called @code{myFunc} with two parameters (of
type @code{bool} and @code{MyEnum} respectively) and returning a value
of type @code{MyReturnType}.  In the function body a local variable is
declared, a conditional action event is called, a global state variable
is set, another function is called, and the return value is set.


Functions are allowed to be recursive, and also mutual recursive
(function @code{f}calling function @code{g} and vice versa), under one
condition: A recursive function must be "tail recursive"; this means
that the recursive call must be the last statement in the function.  The
rationale for this restriction comes from the need for verification: the
generic recursive case cannot be verified.


