@node Namespaces
@section Namespaces

All component, interface, and type definitions can be defined in a
@i{namespace}, which provides name scoping.  The scope can be used when
referring to such a definition.

@subsection Namespace Syntax

A namespace has a name, and within its scope components, interfaces,
types, and sub-namespaces can be defined.

A syntax example:



@example
namespace MyNamespace @{
  extern MyString $std::string$;
  interface MyInterface @{
    enum MyEnumType @{ Val1, Val2, Val3 @};
    in MyEnumType myValuedEvent(MyString s);
    out void myReply();
    behaviour @{
      on myValuedEvent(s) : @{ reply MyEnumType.Val3; @}
    @}
  @}
@}
@end example


In this example namespace @code{MyNamespace} is introduced.  In its scope
data type @code{MyString} and interface @code{MyInterface}are defined.


An example with nested namespaces introduces namespace
@code{Mynamespace1}, and within that (among others) namespace
@code{MyNamespace2}, which itself contains interface @code{MyInterface}:



@example
namespace MyNamespace1 @{
  extern MyString $std::string$;
  namespace MyNamespace2 @{
    interface MyInterface @{
      enum MyEnumType @{ Val1, Val2, Val3 @};
      in MyEnumType myValuedEvent(MyString s);
      out void myReply();
      behaviour @{
         on myValuedEvent(s) : @{ reply MyEnumType.Val3; @}
      @}
    @}
  @}
@}
@end example



@subsubsection Namespace Re-definition
It is allowed to spread the definition of types, interfaces, components,
and sub-namespaces over multiple instances of a namespace scope.  This is
most useful since in a 'real' project definitions are spread over
multiple files.


So



@example
namespace MyNamespace1 @{
  extern MyString $std::string$;
  interface MyInterface @{ ...  @}
@}
@end example


is equivalent to



@example
namespace MyNamespace1 @{
  extern MyString $std::string$;
@}
namespace MyNamespace1 @{
  interface MyInterface @{ ...  @}
@}
@end example



@subsection Referencing
When within namespace @code{MyNamespace}@code{MyThing} is defined, then
outside that namespace it is referred to by prefixing it with the name
of that namespace and a dot, as in: @code{MyNamespace.MyThing}

Within its own namespace the short name @code{MyThing} is to be used.


In complex cases it may be necessary to refer to the @i{global}
namespace which has an empty name; this results in name references
starting with a dot, as can be seen in the following somewhat convoluted
example.



@example
namespace foo @{
  interface I @{
    enum Bool @{F,T@};
    in Bool e();
    out void a();
    behaviour @{
      on e: @{a; reply (Bool.T); @}
    @}
  @}
@}
namespace inner @{
  namespace foo @{
    interface I @{
      enum Bool @{f,t@};
      in Bool e();
      out void a();
      behaviour @{ ....  @}
    @}
  @}
  component space @{
    provides foo.I inner;
    provides .foo.I fooi;
    behaviour @{
      foo.I.Bool inner_state = foo.I.Bool.t;
      .foo.I.Bool foo_state = .foo.I.Bool.T;
      on inner.e(): @{...@}
      on fooi.e(): @{...@}
    @}
  @}
@}
namespace bar @{
  component c @{
    provides foo.I i;
    behaviour @{
      foo.I.Bool state = foo.I.Bool.T;
      on i.e(): @{...@}
    @}
  @}
@}
@end example


which defines:

@itemize

@item interface @code{foo.I} with local enum @code{foo.I.Bool}
@item interface @code{inner.foo.I} with local enum @code{inner.foo.I.Bool}
@item component @code{inner.space}
@item component @code{bar.c}
@end itemize
The two variables defined in component @code{inner.space} have types
@code{foo.I.Bool} and @code{.foo.I.Bool} respectively.  The first type
expands to @code{inner.foo.I.Bool} since it is defined in namespace
@code{inner}.  The starting dot in the second definition prevents this
expansion.

@subsection Shorthand Namespace Syntax
In trivial cases, e.g.  where only one definition is provided within a
namespace, a dot notation can be used.  Using this notation,



@example
namespace MyNamespace1 @{
  namespace MyNamespace2 @{
    extern MyString $std::string$;
  @}
  interface MyInterface @{ ...  @}
@}
@end example


can be written as:



@example
extern MyNamespace1.MyNamespace2.MyString $std::string$;
interface MyNamespace1.MyInterface @{ ...  @}
@end example




@cindex namespace
@cindex Namespace Syntax
@node Well-formedness
@chapter Well-formedness
The syntax as defined in @ref{Dezyne Syntax} defines an asd language
which is not restrictive enough for practical use.  This page describes
a collection of well-formedness checks that are defined on top of the
syntax.  Some of these checks are "common sense", other ones are needed
to define appropriate semantics.

@section Summary
The well-formedness checks in alphabetical order:

