@section Checks
Well-formedness checks on the Behaviour part of a model come in a number
of categories:

@itemize

@item Directional: @i{triggers} and @i{actions} are expected at different places.

@item Nesting: the imperative part of the language (AssignmentStatements, ActionStatements,
FunctionCallStatements) are only allowed in the 'leaves' of the language
constructs.

@item Mixing: The mix of Statements within a CompoundStatements is restricted.

@item Guards: There are some restrictions on what is allowed in a Guard.

@item Functions: a function body should be imperative, and have a well-defined return.

@end itemize
@i{Note: a trigger is an event prefixed by 'on' in the behaviour, an
action is an event inside the body of a trigger.}

Well-formedness checks for a composite Component are:

@itemize

@item Binding: all ports should be bound correctly.

@end itemize

@section Well-formedness Checks -- Top level

@anchor{Interface must define behaviour @i{Sensor}}
@subsection Interface must define behaviour: @i{Sensor}
Interfaces without behaviour are not allowed.  No adequate default
behaviour is available:



@example
 1 interface Sensor @{
 2   in void enable();
 3   in void disable();
 4   out void triggered();
 5   out void disabled();
 6 @}
@end example


This results in the following error message:

@example
1:11: Interface must define behaviour: @i{Sensor}
@end example

@anchor{Interface must define at least one event @i{Sensor}}
@subsection Interface must define at least one event: @i{Sensor}
Completely 'passive' interfaces are not allowed; at least one @b{in} or
@b{out} event is required:



@example
 1 interface Sensor @{
 2   behaviour @{
 3     // ...
 4   @}
 5 @}
@end example


This results in the following error message:

@example
1:11: Interface must define at least one event: @i{Sensor}
@end example

@anchor{Out Event with non void return type is not allowed @i{evt}}
@subsection Out Event with non void return type is not allowed: @i{evt}
Only @i{in} Event can have a return type.



@example
 1 interface Sensor @{
 2   enum Value@{ New, Old @};
 3   in void enable();
 4   in void disable();
 5   out Value triggered();
 6   out void disabled();
 7   ...
 8 @}
@end example


This results in the following error message:

@example
5:13: Out Event with non void return type is not allowed: @i{triggered}
@end example

@anchor{Component with behaviour needs at least one trigger event
@i{Alarm}}
@subsection Component with behaviour needs at least one trigger event: @i{Alarm}
Any Component with a @b{behaviour} specification is supposed to be
'reactive'.  This implies that it should have at least one @b{provides}
Interface with an @b{in} Event, or at least one @b{requires} Interface
with an @b{out} Event.  Such an Event acts as a 'trigger' for the
Component to react on.  So-called 'active' Components are not allowed
(yet) in the ASD language.


An example:



@example
  1 interface Sensor @{
  2   in void activate();
  3   in void deactivate();
  4   behaviour @{ ...  @}
  5 @}
  6
  7 component Alarm @{
  8   requires Sensor sensor;
  9   behaviour @{ ...  @}
 10 @}
@end example


Another example:



@example
  1 interface Siren @{
  2   out void start();
  3   out void stop();
  4   behaviour @{ ...  @}
  5 @}
  6
  7 component Alarm @{
  8   provides Siren siren;
  9   behaviour @{ ...  @}
 10 @}
@end example


Both examples result in the following error message:

@example
7:11: Component with behaviour needs at least one trigger event: @i{Alarm}
@end example

@anchor{Component with behaviour must have at least one provides port
@i{Alarm}}
@subsection Component with behaviour must have at least one provides port: @i{Alarm}
Any Component with a @b{behaviour} specification must have a provides
port through which the Component is activated.


An example:



@example
 1 component Alarm @{
 2   requires Sensor sensor;
 3   behaviour @{ ...  @}
 4 @}
@end example


The examples result in the following error message:

@example
1:11: Component with behaviour must have at least one provides port: @i{Alarm}
@end example

@section Well-formedness Checks -- Directional

@anchor{Event is not an action @i{console.arm}}
@subsection Event is not an action: @i{console.arm}
Event @i{console.arm} is used as @i{action}, but is introduced as a
@i{trigger}.


In an InterfaceModel this indicates the Event is defined as an @b{in}
event.


In a DesignModel this indicates that either it is an @b{in} Event of a
@b{provides} interface of the design, or an @b{out} Event of a
@b{requires} interface.

@anchor{Event is not a valid trigger @i{console.detected}}
@subsection Event is not a valid trigger: @i{console.detected}
Event @i{console.detected} is used as @i{trigger}, but is introduced as
an @i{action}.


In an InterfaceModel this indicates the Event is defined as an @b{out}
event.


In a DesignModel this indicates that either it is an @b{out} Event of a
@b{provides} interface of the design, or an @b{in} Event of a
@b{requires} interface.

@section Well-formedness Checks -- Nesting
The nesting of language constructs is restricted.  When we conceptually
'expand' CompoundStatements, two Statement levels can be identified:

@itemize

@item The outer level we call @b{declarative}.  It consists of exactly
one OnEventStatement, optionally guarded at either side with
GuardedStatements and at most one BlockingStatement.  Valid examples
are:

@end itemize



@example
 1 on sensor.triggered(): @{ ...  @}
 2 [guard1] [guard2] on sensor.triggered(): @{ ...  @}
 3 [guard1] on sensor.triggered(): [guard2] @{ ...  @}
 4 on sensor.triggered(): [guard1] [guard2] @{ ...  @}
 5 [guard1] blocking [guard2] on sensor.triggered(): @{ ...  @}
 6 blocking [guard1] on sensor.triggered(): [guard2] @{ ...  @}
 7 on sensor.triggered(): [guard1] [guard2] blocking @{ ...  @}
@end example



@itemize

@item The inner level we call @b{imperative}.  It consists of ActionStatements
and AssignmentStatements.  Imperative statements are only allowed within
a declarative context:

@end itemize



@example
 1 [state.Armed]
 2 @{
 3   on sensor.triggered():
 4   @{
 5     // the imperative part:
 6     console.detected();
 7     state = States.Triggered;
 8   @}
 9 @}
@end example



@anchor{AssignmentStatement only allowed within OnEventStatement}
@subsection AssignmentStatement only allowed within OnEventStatement
An AssignmentStatement occurred outside the scope of a declarative
context:



@example
 1 [state.Armed]
 2 @{
 3   state = States.Triggered;
 4 @}
@end example


This results in the following error message:

@example
3:3: Well-formedness error: AssignmentStatement only allowed within OnEventStatement
@end example

@anchor{ActionStatement only allowed within OnEventStatement}
@subsection ActionStatement only allowed within OnEventStatement
An ActionStatement occurred outside the scope of a declarative context:



@example
 1 [state.Disarming]
 2 @{
 3   console.detected();
 4 @}
@end example


This results in the following error message:

@example
3:3: Well-formedness error: ActionStatement only allowed within OnEventStatement
@end example

@anchor{OnEventStatement not allowed within other OnEventStatement}
@subsection OnEventStatement not allowed within other OnEventStatement
A second OnEventStatement occurred in the declarative context:



@example
 1 on console.arm():
 2 @{
 3   [state.Disarming]
 4   @{
 5     on sensor.triggered():
 6     @{ ...  @}
 7   @}
 8 @}
@end example


This results in the following error message:

@example
5:5: Well-formedness error: OnEventStatement not allowed within other OnEventStatement
@end example

@anchor{BlockingStatement not allowed within other BlockingStatement}
@subsection BlockingStatement not allowed within other BlockingStatement
A second BlockingStatement occurred in the declarative context:



@example
 1 blocking on console.arm():
 2 @{
 3   [state.Disarming]
 4   @{
 5     blocking
 6     @{ ...  @}
 7   @}
 8 @}
@end example


This results in the following error message:

@example
5:5: Well-formedness error: BlockingStatement not allowed within other BlockingStatement
@end example

@anchor{BlockingStatement not allowed in interface behaviour}
@subsection BlockingStatement not allowed in interface behaviour
Events handling can be 'blocking' in component behaviour only.  It is not
allowed in interfaces.  So:



@example
 1 interface Sensor @{
 2   in void enable();
 3   in void disable();
 4   behaviour @{
 5     on enable: @{ ....  @}
 6     blocking on disable: @{ ...  @}
 7   @}
 8 @}
@end example


results in the following error message:

@example
6:5: Well-formedness error: BlockingStatement not allowed in interface behaviour
@end example

@anchor{BlockingStatement not allowed with multiple provides ports}
@subsection BlockingStatement not allowed with multiple provides ports
A component with more than one provides port is not allowed to block
events, due to implementation restrictions.  So:



@example
  1 interface Sensor @{
  2   in void activate();
  3   out void activated();
  4   behaviour @{
  5     on activate: @{@}
  6     on inevitable: activated;
  7   @}
  8 @}
  9
 10 interface Test @{
 11   in void test();
 12   behaviour @{
 13     on test: @{@}
 14   @}
 15 @}
 16
 17 component SensorComp @{
 18   provides Sensor sensor1;
 19   provides Test test;
 20   requires Sensor sensor2;
 21   behaviour @{
 22     blocking on sensor1.activate(): sensor2.activate();
 23     on sensor2.activated(): @{ sensor1.activated(); sensor1.reply(); @}
 24     on test.test(): @{@}
 25   @}
 26 @}
@end example


results in the following error message:

@example
22:5: Well-formedness error: BlockingStatement not allowed with multiple provides ports
@end example

@section Well-formedness Checks -- Mixing
A behaviour description introduces a sequence of statements.  A statement
itself can be a CompoundStatement, which is a sequence of statements
between curly braces.


In order to be able to define clear semantics, there are some
restrictions on the mix of statements in such a sequence.

@anchor{Only declarative Statement allowed here}
@subsection Only declarative Statement allowed here
If a sequence starts with a declarative Statement (as in
@i{[state.Armed]....}or @i{on console.disarm(): ...}), all other
statements shall be declarative Statements.

@anchor{Only imperative Statement allowed here}
@subsection Only imperative Statement allowed here
If a sequence starts with either an imperative Statement (as in @i{state
= States.Armed;} or @i{siren.turnon();}), all other statements must also
be imperative.

@anchor{Otherwise guard combined with second otherwise is not allowed}
@subsection Otherwise guard combined with second otherwise is not allowed
An @i{otherwise} guard catches the remaining cases for a list of guards.
For that reason it is not allowed to have more than one @i{otherwise}
statement in a list.  So:



@example
 1 on console.arm():
 2 @{
 3   [sounding] sounding = false;
 4   [otherwise] sounding = true;
 5   [otherwise] illegal;
 6 @}
 7
@end example


will result in the following error message:

@example
4:4: Well-formedness error: Otherwise guard combined with second otherwise is not allowed
5:3: Well-formedness error: Second otherwise defined here
@end example

@anchor{Otherwise guard combined with non GuardedStatement is not
allowed}
@subsection Otherwise guard combined with non GuardedStatement is not allowed
An @i{otherwise} guard catches the remaining cases for a list of guards.
For that reason it is not allowed combine an @i{otherwise} statement
with a non-guarded statement.  So:



@example
 1 on console.arm(): sounding = false;
 2 [otherwise] @{ on console.disarm(): sounding = true; @}
 3
@end example


will result in the following error message:

@example
4:2: Well-formedness error: Otherwise guard combined with non GuardedStatement is not allowed
1:2: Well-formedness error: non GuardedStatement defined here
@end example

@anchor{Illegal must be the only Statement in a compound}
@subsection Illegal must be the only Statement in a compound
An @i{illegal} ActionStatement must occur on its own; no other
ActionStatements or AssignmentStatements are allowed.  That also applies
if the @i{illegal} occurs in a nested CompoundStatement:



@example
 1 on console.arm():
 2 @{
 3   @{
 4     @{ illegal; @}
 5   @}
 6   sounding = true;
 7 @}
@end example


This results in the following error message:

@example
4:7: Well-formedness error: Illegal must be the only Statement in a compound
@end example


Using @i{illegal} within a conditional statement @i{is} allowed.  Also
the condition may be accompanied by other action statements, e.g:



@example
 1 on console.arm():
 2 @{
 3   s = sensor.enable();
 4   if (s.NOK) @{
 5     illegal;
 6   @}
 7 @}
@end example

@anchor{Illegal is not allowed in if-then-else statements}
@subsection Illegal is not allowed in if-then-else statements
In an Interface declaration an Event can only be declared @i{illegal} in
a direct way.  This is due to the declarative character of interfaces.
To be more specific, it must not occur in an if-then-else construct.  An
example:



@example
 1 bool b = true;
 2 on arm:
 3 @{
 4   if (b) @{ illegal; @}
 5   else @{ state = States.Armed; @}
 6 @}
@end example


This results in the following error message:

@example
4:12: Well-formedness error: Illegal is not allowed in if-then-else statements
@end example

@anchor{Illegal is not allowed in functions}
@subsection Illegal is not allowed in functions
In an Interface declaration an Event can only be declared @i{illegal} in
a direct way.  This is due to the declarative character of interfaces.
To be more specific, it must not occur in a function body.  An example:



@example
 1 void ill()
 2 @{
 3   illegal;
 4 @}
 5 on arm:
 6 @{
 7   ill();
 8 @}
@end example


This results in the following error message:

@example
3:3: Well-formedness error: Illegal is not allowed in functions
@end example

@section Well-formedness Checks -- Reply
A 'reply' is required in the handling of a valued (i.e.  non-void) event.
It is also required in case an event (that might be void) is used in
'blocking' mode; in that case the occurrence of the reply might be
postponed.  In general this is hard to check statically.  What can be
checked is described below.

@anchor{Reply not allowed on 'requires' Port 'sensor'}
@subsection Reply not allowed on 'requires' Port: 'sensor'
A 'reply' which is issued to release a blocking event refers to the
event's port.  Since blocking is effective on 'provides' ports only, a
well-formedness error is issued when a 'requires' port name is used.  An
example:



@example
  1 component Test @{
  2   provides Start start;
  3   requires Sensor sensor;
  4   behaviour @{
  5     on start.start(): @{ sensor.activate(); @}
  6     blocking on start.stop(): @{ sensor.activate(); @}
  7     on sensor.deactivated(): @{ sensor.reply(); @}
  8   @}
  9 @}
@end example


This results in the following error message:

@example
7:32: Well-formedness error: Reply not allowed on 'requires' Port: 'sensor'
@end example

@section Well-formedness Checks -- Valued Actions and Functions
Both Actions and Functions can be valued, and as such are considered to
be expressions.  The places where they can be called are severely
restricted.  The main reason is that Actions and Functions (at least the
ones containing Actions) cause a side effect.  The order of evaluation
in complex expressions becomes an issue when side effects are
considered.  In order to exclude that, valued Actions and Function calls
can only occur in isolation at the right hand side of an assignment.


An extra restriction to this rule is put on the initial value of a
global variable in a behaviour.  Such an expression can not contain
Actions and Functions at all, since Actions are only allowed within an
OnEventStatement.

@anchor{Actions are not allowed here}
@subsection Actions are not allowed here
An Action is used in a complex expression.



@example
  1 interface Sensor @{
  2   enum Status @{ OK, NOK @};
  3   in Status enable();
  4 @}
  5 component Alarm @{
  6   provides Console console;
  7   requires Sensor sensor;
  8   behaviour @{
  9     ....
 10     bool b = true;
 11     on console.arm():
 12     @{
 13       if (sensor.enable() == Sensor.Status.OK) @{
 14         state = States.Armed;
 15       @}
 16       bool b = sensor.enable();
 17       bool b = b || sensor.enable();
 18     @}
 19   @}
 20 @}
@end example


This results in the following error messages:

@example
13:10: Well-formedness error: Actions are not allowed here
17:20: Well-formedness error: Actions are not allowed here
@end example
The call of the @i{sensor.enable()} action on line 16 is the only
acceptable one.


Action is used as initial value of a global variable.



@example
  1 interface Sensor @{
  2   enum Status @{ OK, NOK @};
  3   in Status enable();
  4 @}
  5 component Alarm @{
  6   provides Console console;
  7   requires Sensor sensor;
  8   behaviour @{
  9     ...
 10     Sensor.Status st = sensor.enable();
 11     on console.arm():
 12     @{
 13       ...
 14     @}
 15   @}
 16 @}
@end example


This results in the following error message:

@example
10:24: Well-formedness error: Actions are not allowed here
@end example

@anchor{Function calls are not allowed here}
@subsection Function calls are not allowed here
A Function call is used in a complex expression.



@example
  1 interface Sensor @{
  2   enum Status @{ OK, NOK @};
  3   in Status enable();
  4 @}
  5 component Alarm @{
  6   provides Console console;
  7   requires Sensor sensor;
  8   behaviour @{
  9     ....
 10     bool ok() @{
 11       return (enab() == OK);
 12     @}
 13     Sensor.Status enab() @{
 14       Sensor.Status r = sensor.enable();
 15       return r;
 16     @}
 17     ...
 18   @}
 19 @}
@end example


This results in the following error message:

@example
11:14: Well-formedness error: Function calls are not allowed here
@end example

@anchor{Function value discarded @i{negate}}
@subsection Function value discarded: @i{negate}
A valued Function is called without assigning its return value.



@example
  1 ...
  2 bool negate(bool b)
  3 @{
  4   return !b;
  5 @}
  6 void test(bool b)
  7 @{
  8   negate(b);
  9 @}
 10 ...
@end example


This results in the following error message:

@example
8:7: Well-formedness error: Function value discarded: @i{negate}
@end example

@anchor{Action value discarded @i{enable}}
@subsection Action value discarded: @i{enable}
A valued Function is called without assigning its return value.  An
example:



@example
  1 interface Sensor @{
  2   enum Status @{ OK, NOK @};
  3   in Status enable();
  4 @}
  5 component Alarm @{
  6   provides Console console;
  7   requires Sensor sensor;
  8   behaviour @{
  9     ....
 10     on console.arm():
 11     @{
 12       sensor.enable();
 13     @}
 14   @}
 15 @}
@end example


This results in the following error message:

@example
12:7: Well-formedness error: Action value discarded: @i{enable}
@end example

@section Well-formedness Checks -- Injection

@anchor{Injected Port has out event @i{i}}
@subsection Injected Port has out event: @i{i}
When a Component has a required injected Port, the corresponding
Interface shall not have out events.  An example:



@example
 1 interface Intf @{
 2   in void evt();
 3   out void notif();
 4 @}
 5
 6 component Comp @{
 7   requires injected Intf i;
 8   .....
 9 @}
@end example


The following error message will be issued:

@example
7:26: Well-formedness error: Injected Port has out event: @i{i}
@end example

@section Well-formedness Checks -- Binding
In a composite Component the Component's ports and all sub Component
ports must be bound correctly.


We'll use the following (somewhat artificial) example to elaborate on
binding errors below:



@example
  1 import Console;
  2 import Alarm_Impl;
  3 import Sensor_Impl;
  4 import Siren_Impl;
  5
  6 component AlarmSystem
  7 @{
  8   provides Console console;
  9   provides Console consoleAlt;
 10
 11   system
 12   @{
 13     Alarm_Impl alarm;
 14     Sensor_Impl sensor;
 15     Siren_Impl siren;
 16
 17     // bindings .....
 18   @}
 19 @}
@end example


Bindings in which 'wildcards' are involved will be described at the end
of this section.

@anchor{Port is not bound @i{console}}
@subsection Port is not bound: @i{console}
No binding is specified for a port of a composite Component.  If no
bindings are added in the AlarmSystem Component above, the following
error message will be issued (among others):

@example
8:19: Well-formedness error: Port is not bound: @i{console}
9:19: Well-formedness error: Port is not bound: @i{consoleAlt}
@end example

@anchor{Port is not bound @i{alarm.console}}
@subsection Port is not bound: @i{alarm.console}
No binding is specified for a port of a sub Component.  If no bindings
are added in the AlarmSystem Component above, the following error
message will be issued (among others):

@example
12:16: Well-formedness error: Port is not bound: @i{alarm.console}
@end example

@anchor{Port is bound twice @i{alarm.console}}
@subsection Port is bound twice: @i{alarm.console}
More than one binding is specified for a port of a composite Component
or one of its sub Components.  If line 17 in the AlarmSystem Component
above is followed by



@example
 18 console <=> alarm.console;
 19 alarm.sensor <=> sensor.sensor;
 20 consoleAlt <=> alarm.console;
@end example


the following error message will be issued (among others):

@example
20:20: Well-formedness error: Port is bound twice: @i{alarm.console}
@end example

@anchor{Binding directions do not match}
@subsection Binding directions do not match
The directions of the left and right port mentioned in the binding do
not match.  The following constructs are allowed:

@itemize

@item When binding a port of the Component to a port of a sub Component, the
directions must be the same:

@itemize

@item @b{provides} binds to @b{provides}
@item @b{requires} binds to @b{requires}
@end itemize

@item When binding a port of the Component to another port of the Component
(does this make sense??), the directions must be the opposite:

@itemize

@item @b{provides} binds to @b{requires} or vice versa.

@end itemize

@item When binding a port of a sub Component to a port of another (or the same)
sub Component, the directions must be the opposite:

@itemize

@item @b{provides} binds to @b{requires} or vice versa.

@end itemize

@end itemize
If line 17 in the AlarmSystem Component above is followed by



@example
 18 console <=> consoleAlt;
@end example


the following error message will be issued (among others):

@example
18:5: Well-formedness error: Binding directions do not match
@end example

@anchor{Binding two wildcards is not allowed}
@subsection Binding two wildcards is not allowed
When a 'wildcard' is used in a binding the other side of the binding
cannot have a wildcard also.


An example:



@example
  1 component Sys @{
  2   provides Console console;
  3   system @{
  4     Logger logger;
  5     SubSystem sub;
  6     ...
  7     logger.* <=> sub.*;
  8     ...
  9   @}
 10 @}
@end example


This will result in the following error message:

@example
7:14: Well-formedness error: Binding two wildcards is not allowed
@end example

@anchor{Component is part of a cyclic binding}
@subsection Component is part of a cyclic binding
We can define communication 'direction' for bindings as follows:

@itemize

@item For two sub components communicating: the @code{requires} port directs to
the @code{provides} port in the binding.

@item For port forwarding (an external port is forwarded to a sub-component port) or vice versa:
A @code{provides} external port directs to a @code{provides}
sub-component port, and a @code{requires} sub-component port directs to
a @code{requires} external port.

@end itemize
To prevent component re-entrancy and guarantee run-to-completion
semantics, cycles in 'directed' communication are not allowed within a
system component.


In the most trivial example, which creates a one-component cycle:

@example
  1 component Comp @{
  2   provides Intf prov;
  3   requires Intf req;
  4 @}
  5
  6 component Sys @{
  7   system @{
  8     Comp c;
  9     c.prov <=> c.req;
 10   @}
 11 @}
@end example


the following error message will be issued:

@example
8:5: Well-formedness error: Component is part of a cyclic binding: @i{c}
@end example


A more elaborate example creates a cycle over three components:

@example
  1 component Comp1 @{
  2   provides Intf p;
  3   requires Intf r;
  4 @}
  5
  6 component Comp2 @{
  7   provides Intf p1;
  8   provides Intf p2;
  9   requires Intf r1;
 10   requires Intf r2;
 11 @}
 12
 13 component Sys @{
 14   provides Intf p1;
 15   provides Intf p2;
 16
 17   requires Intf r1;
 18   requires Intf r2;
 19
 20   system @{
 21     Comp2 c21;
 22     Comp2 c22;
 23     Comp1 c11;
 24     Comp1 c12;
 25
 26     p1 <=> c21.p1;
 27     p2 <=> c22.p1;
 28     c21.r1 <=> c11.p;
 29     c21.r2 <=> c12.p;
 30     c22.r1 <=> c21.p2;
 31     c22.r2 <=> r2;
 32
 33     c11.r <=> r1;
 34     c12.r <=> c22.p2;
 35   @}
 36 @}
@end example


As a result the following error messages will be issued:

@example
21:5: Well-formedness error: Component is part of a cyclic binding: @i{c21}
22:5: Well-formedness error: Component is part of a cyclic binding: @i{c22}
24:5: Well-formedness error: Component is part of a cyclic binding: @i{c12}
@end example

@anchor{Wildcard can be bound to a provided port only}
@subsection Wildcard can be bound to a provided port only
Since @b{injected} Ports are always @b{requires}Ports, and a wildcard is
used to bind such a Port, the other side of a wildcard binding must be a
@b{provides} Port.  In this example:



@example
  1 component Comp @{
  2   requires injected Logger logger;
  3   .....
  4 @}
  5
  6 component MyLogger @{
  7   requires Logger logger;
  8   ...
  9 @}
 10
 11 component Sys @{
 12   provides Console console;
 13   system @{
 14     MyLogger myLogger;
 15     SubSystem sub;
 16     ...
 17     myLogger.logger <=> *;
 18   @}
 19 @}
@end example


the following error message will be issued:

@example
17:20: Well-formedness error: Wildcard can be bound to a provided port only
@end example

@anchor{System composition is recursive}
@subsection System composition is recursive
A system component may instantiate an arbitrary set of other components,
which can be system components themselves.  It is not allowed to have a
self-instance neither directly nor indirectly, since that would lead to
an infinite tree of components.


In the example below five system components are defined that have mutual
instances.  Component C1 instantiates C3, which instantiates C4, which
instantiates C1.

@example
  1 component C1 @{
  2   system @{
  3     C2 c2;
  4     C3 c3;
  5   @}
  6 @}
  7
  8 component C2 @{
  9   system @{
 10     C5 c5;
 11   @}
 12 @}
 13
 14 component C3 @{
 15   system @{
 16     C4 c4;
 17     C2 c2;
 18   @}
 19 @}
 20
 21 component C4 @{
 22   system @{
 23     C1 c1;
 24   @}
 25 @}
 26
 27 component C5 @{
 28   system @{ @} // an empty system
 29 @}
@end example


All components involved in the cyclic instantiation will be report in
the error messages:

@example
1:11: Well-formedness error: System composition is recursive: 'C1'
14:11: Well-formedness error: System composition is recursive: 'C3'
21:11: Well-formedness error: System composition is recursive: 'C4'
@end example

@anchor{External port must be bound to external port @i{r2}}
@subsection External port must be bound to external port: @i{r2}
There is a restriction in the binding of external ports: when an
external requires port of a system Component is bound, the other side of
the binding must be an external requires port also (this is only
possible when that is a port of a sub Component)


In the example below some errors are reported.

@example
  1 interface I @{
  2   in void e();
  3   behaviour @{
  4     on e: @{@}
  5   @}
  6 @}
  7
  8 component C1 @{
  9   provides I p;
 10   requires external I r1;
 11   requires external I r2;
 12   behaviour @{
 13     on p.e(): @{@}
 14   @}
 15 @}
 16
 17 component C2 @{
 18   provides I p;
 19   behaviour @{
 20     on p.e(): @{@}
 21   @}
 22 @}
 23
 24 component S1 @{
 25   provides I p;
 26   requires I r;
 27   system @{
 28     C1 c1;
 29     C2 c2;
 30     p <=> c1.p;
 31     c1.r1 <=> r;
 32     c1.r2 <=> c2.p;
 33   @}
 34 @}
 35
 36 component S2 @{
 37   provides I p1;
 38   provides I p2;
 39   requires external I r1;
 40   requires external I r2;
 41   system @{
 42     S1 s1;
 43     p1 <=> s1.p;
 44     p2 <=> r2;
 45     r1 <=> s1.r;
 46   @}
 47 @}
@end example


the following error message will be issued on @i{S2}:

@example
44:12: Well-formedness error: External port must be bound to external port: @i{r2}
45:5: Well-formedness error: External port must be bound to external port: @i{r1}
@end example

@section Well-formedness Checks -- Functions

@itemize

@item A Function body can only contain imperative statements, including
ActionStatements.  See the sections on 'Mixing' and 'Direction' above.

@item A valued Function is required to have an explicit return.

@item A return is only allowed in a function body.

@item A recursive Function is required to be tail recursive

@end itemize

@anchor{Function does not return a value in all cases}
@subsection Function does not return a value in all cases
A valued Function should return a value using the ReturnStatement.  An
error is issued when a return is not guaranteed.  An example:



@example
 1 bool func()
 2 @{
 3   if (a && b)
 4   @{ return true; @}
 5   else if (c)
 6   @{ illegal; @}
 7 @}
@end example


For this code fragment the following error message will be issued:

@example
1:10: Well-formedness error: Function does not return a value in all cases: func
@end example

@anchor{Return Statement not allowed here}
@subsection Return Statement not allowed here
A @b{return} Statement is restricted to Function bodies.  So



@example
 1 on sensor.disabled():
 2 @{
 3   [sounding]
 4   @{
 5     return; // triggers an error
 6   @}
 7 @}
@end example


This will cause the following error to be reported:

@example
5:5: Well-formedness error: Return Statement not allowed here
@end example

@anchor{Statement violates tail recursion in recursive Function}
@subsection Statement violates tail recursion in recursive Function
A function that is recursive must be tail recursive, i.e.  in its body
any recursive function call shall not be followed by other
Statements.  So



@example
  1 component Sensor @{
  2   ...
  3   behaviour @{
  4     ...
  5     void f() @{
  6       bool b = false;
  7       if (b) @{
  8         f();
  9         b = true;
 10       @}
 11     @}
 12   @}
 13 @}
@end example


will result in the following error message:

@example
9:9: Well-formedness error: Statement violates tail recursion in recursive Function
@end example
Remark: two functions @i{f} and @i{g} that are defined in terms of each
other are considered (mutual) recursive also.

@section Well-formedness Checks -- Data Parameters
The restrictions on Data parameters are summarised here.

@anchor{Parameter type must be a data type Code}
@subsection Parameter type must be a data type: Code
All event parameters specified in an event declaration must be data
parameters; in other words, they must have a data type.  An example:



@example
  1 interface Sensor @{
  2   enum Code @{ ok, nok @};
  3   in Code activate(Code c);
  4   behaviour @{ ...  @}
  5 @}
@end example


This will result in the following error message:

@example
3:20: Well-formedness error: Parameter type must be a data type: 'Code'
@end example

@anchor{Out Parameter is not allowed for out Event}
@subsection Out Parameter is not allowed for out Event
An out Event is not allowed to have an out Data Parameter.  This example:



@example
 1 interface Sensor @{
 2   extern INT $int$;
 3   in void enable();
 4   in void disable();
 5   out void triggered(out INT value);
 6   out void disabled();
 7 @}
@end example


will result in the following error message:

@example
5:30: Well-formedness error: Out Parameter is not allowed for out Event: value
@end example

@anchor{Inout Parameter is not allowed for out Event}
@subsection Inout Parameter is not allowed for out Event
An out Event is not allowed to have an inout Data Parameter.  An example:



@example
 1 interface Sensor @{
 2   extern INT $int$;
 3   in void enable();
 4   in void disable();
 5   out void triggered();
 6   out void disabled(inout INT dis);
 7 @}
@end example


will result in the following error message:

@example
6:31: Well-formedness error: Inout Parameter is not allowed for out Event: dis
@end example

@anchor{Parameter Binding not allowed here}
@subsection Parameter Binding not allowed here
Parameter binding, which is the binding of a global data variable 'D' to
an event parameter 'p' using the 'p <- D' construct, is allowed in an
'on event' context only.  Any other location is reported as an
error.  So:



@example
  1 extern xint $int$;
  2 component Test @{
  3   provides Intf intf;
  4   behaviour @{
  5     xint NR;
  6     on intf.evt(number):
  7       fn(number <- NR);
  8
  9     void fn(xint i) @{ ...  @}
 10   @}
 11 @}
@end example


will result in the following error message:

@example
7:17: Well-formedness error: '<-' not allowed here
@end example

